{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11354"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11354"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.49,0.07,0.23,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78855"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3999"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1362"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44357"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78855"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman is being investigated for Cushings syndrome. Exogenous steroid intake by the patient has been excluded. Midnight salivary cortisol levels and a low-dose dexamethasone suppression test have confirmed hypercortisolaemia, and a plasma adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) level has returned at 50 pg/mL [10 - 60]. A high-dose dexamethasone suppression test has been performed and demonstrates a reduction in plasma cortisol level by 75%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathology in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)-secreting tumour","Pituitary corticotroph adenoma","Small cell lung carcinoma","Adrenal adenoma","Bilateral adrenal hyperplasia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor cases such as this, working through the results one step at a time is crucial:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypercortisolaemia has been satisfactorily shown by two cross-confirmatory tests, establishing Cushing\u0027s syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn inappropriately normal ACTH level despite hypercortisolaemia signals ACTH-dependent disease, removing adrenal pathology from the likely differentials and leaving either pituitary pathology or ectopic ACTH production as the likely underlying cause. A potential clue toward a pituitary aetiology is noted here: with ACTH-secreting tumours, the serum ACTH level is usually very high - often several times the upper limit of normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high-dose dexamethasone test is predicated on the premise that most pituitary corticotroph tumours retain some responsiveness to negative glucocorticoid feedback (albeit reduced), whereas ectopic ACTH-secreting tumors typically do not. Therefore, high-dose dexamethasone will suppress cortisol levels in pituitary-driven pathology (the standard threshold is a reduction in cortisol by at least 50%) but not in cases of ectopic ACTH-secreting tissue. In this case, a positive result has returned, which suggests a pituitary location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the best answer is hypersecretory \u003Cstrong\u003Epituitary corticotroph adenoma \u003C/strong\u003E(i.e. Cushing \u003Cem\u003Edisease\u003C/em\u003E). This might be further investigated by performing another cross-confirmatory test such as a corticotropin-releasing hormone test, but an MRI pituitary is certainly in this patient\u0027s future to guide potential trans-sphenoidal pituitary surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E bilateral adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E are examples of ACTH\u003Cem\u003E-independent\u003C/em\u003E disease, which this patient\u0027s ACTH level essentially excludes. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cell lung carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is among the commonest ectopic ACTH-secreting tumours; as they are unaffected by the negative feedback of dexamethasone, the high-dose suppression test would not have been positive. \u003Cstrong\u003ECRH-secreting tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are vanishingly rare, and tend to behave like ectopic ACTH-secreting tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A positive high-dose dexamethasone suppression test in Cushing syndrome suggests pituitary pathology."],"references":["Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, Boyce A, Chrousos G, Corpas E et al. Endotext [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278943/","Barbot M, Zilio M, Scaroni C. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: Overview of clinical presentation, diagnostic tools and complications. Best Pract Res Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2020;34(2):101380. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32165101/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11354"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64204"},"attributes":